StructureDefinition-q

source file: source/pages/_includes/q-intro.md

The Argonaut Q Profile sets the minimum expectations for the Questionnaire resource to record, search and fetch Questionnaire for simple assessments, surveys, etc as defined in this implementation guide

Scope and Usage

The Argonaut Questionnaire resource supports:

  • Instructions for Subjects/Provider administrator
  • Instructions for the Providers (e.g, Scoring instructions)
  • Text based questions
    • Including standardized concepts like LOINC
  • Answers
    • T/F, multiple choice (Including standardized concepts like LOINC)
    • Short answer, narrative and other answer types.

  • Provisions for

    • Associating numeric scores for each group of questions or each question or each answer choice. (How to calculate the total scores can be described as provider instructions )
    • Whether the question is required
    • Whether the answer choice is excludes other choices ( for example, a choice of ‘none of the above’).
    • Whether the item (for example, provider instructions is hidden)
    • Indication for how much time is allowed for the questionnaire, group of questions or each question.

Mandatory Data Elements and Terminology

The following data-elements are mandatory:

Each Questionnaire must have:

  1. An absolute URI that is used to identify this assessment form when it is referenced by a response (required by SDC )
  2. A human friendly title
  3. The form’s status (base specification requirement)
  4. An identifier to link to the response in a QuestionnaireResponse resource (base specification requirement)
  5. A questions type including if a display only question grouping elements (base specification requirement)

The system Must Support if available:

  1. Argonaut Questionnaire Score Extension for use on all answer types and choices (not just codings).
  2. Argonaut Questionnaire Time Limit Extension for indicating the duration allowed for all or parts of the assessment.
  3. Questionnaire Hidden Extension for indicating that the item should not be displayed to the user.
  4. Questionnaire Option Exclusive Extension for indicating that if this option is selected, no other options may be selected.
  5. A version of the assessment
  6. A description of the assessment
  7. A standard concept code (e.g., LOINC) for the question or questions
  8. Text for:
    1. the Question (including prefixes such as numbering or lettering)
    2. Instructions to the Subject/Provider administrator and or scorer
  9. A required flag
  10. A repeat flag
  11. Choice list:
    1. as a contained valueset of standard concepts
    2. or as an enumerated list
  12. Nesting or grouping of questions
  13. the questionnaire’s context for categorizing and grouping for searches

Additional Profile specific implementation guidance:

  1. All ValueSets referenced by the .options element are contained resources in the Questionnaire and require a ValueSet.expansion. This ensures that the Questionnaire will not adopt a new version of the referenced value set without revising the Questionnaire to point to that new version - putting the author of the Questionnaire in control of any changes.

  2. boolean vs choice - In a scenario where the end user has to select simple true/false or active/inactive states the booleanitem answer type (e.g, a checkbox control) is appropriate. Where two alternative answers can’t be handled with a simple checkbox then a choice item answer type is needed. For example, for assigning numeric score values to the individual yes or no answers.
  3. text vs string item types - string item answer types are typically limited to a single line and correspond to the the HTML5 <input> element type “text”. The Questionnaire text item answer types are intended for multiline answers and correspond to the HTML5 <textarea> form attribute.

Examples

  • Sampler - a Sample form using all the supported question types
  • PHQ-9 - An example demonstrating the use of contained value sets for answer choices, decimal scores associated with each value within the valueset, the hidden extension to indicate that provider instruction should not be displayed to the end user.
  • AUDIT - An example multiple choice form demonstrating the use of contained value sets for answer choices, decimal scores associated with each value within the valueset, the hidden extension to indicate that provider instruction should not be displayed to the end user.
  • DAST - An example multiple choice form demonstrating the use of inline codings for answer choices, decimal scores associated with each coding, the hidden extension to indicate that provider instruction should not be displayed to the end user.
  • Housing -An example multiple choice form demonstrating the use of inline strings for answer choices, the hidden extension to indicate that provider instruction should not be displayed to the end user, an ‘any of’ choice option with the the exclusive extension for one of the choices.
  • ASQ3 - An example multiple choice form demonstrating the use of inline codings for answer choices, decimal scores associated with each coding, the hidden extension to indicate that provider instruction should not be displayed to the end user.
